    <section class="section">
      <div class="section-label">
        <span class="num">01 /</span> THE BASICS
      </div>
      <h2 class="section-title">
        What the <span class="red">veto session</span> is and why it mattered yesterday.
      </h2>
      <p class="section-deck">
        Virginia's governor has three options for every bill the General
        Assembly sends her: sign, veto, or return it with <em
          >recommended amendments</em
        >. That third option is what forced lawmakers back to Richmond.
      </p>

      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          Spanberger returned <strong>176 bills</strong> with recommended changes
          before her April 13 deadline, on top of vetoing eight. When she sends a
          bill back, the legislature has one chance to decide what to do with her
          suggestions. That chance was yesterday.
        </p>
        <p>
          Lawmakers had three moves on each amendment: <strong>accept</strong>
          with a simple majority, <strong>reject</strong> by majority or by simply
          refusing to take it up, or <strong>override</strong> with a two-thirds supermajority
          in both chambers. Any emergency clause the governor added requires a steeper
          <strong>four-fifths</strong> vote to survive.
        </p>
        <p>
          Rejection doesn't kill a bill. It sends the <em>original text</em>
          back to the governor's desk, where she has about thirty days to sign it,
          veto it, or let it become law without a signature. That's where we are now
          on every rejected package below.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="process">
        <div class="process-step">
          <div class="process-num">STEP 01</div>
          <div class="process-head">GA passes bill</div>
          <div class="process-body">
            House and Senate reconcile, send enrolled text to the Executive
            Mansion.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="process-step">
          <div class="process-num">STEP 02</div>
          <div class="process-head">Governor amends</div>
          <div class="process-body">
            Instead of signing or vetoing, Spanberger returns the bill with
            "recommended" changes.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="process-step">
          <div class="process-num">STEP 03</div>
          <div class="process-head">Reconvened vote</div>
          <div class="process-body">
            April 22 one-day session. Each chamber votes accept / reject, or
            "passes by" with no vote at all.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="process-step">
          <div class="process-num">STEP 04</div>
          <div class="process-head">Back to the gov</div>
          <div class="process-body">
            Rejected bills return in their original form. She signs, vetoes, or
            lets them become law.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- THE 9 BILL CARDS -->
    <section class="section section-wide">
      <div class="section-label">
        <span class="num">02 /</span> THE SIX GUN PACKAGES
      </div>
      <h2 class="section-title">
        Every gun bill, every <span class="red">amendment</span>, every next
        step.
      </h2>
      <p class="section-deck">
        Six gun-bill packages across ten individual bill numbers. Four are
        confrontational (bans, carry restrictions, age hikes, hospital
        carve-outs). Two are incremental (storage definition, buyback program
        language). Every one of them is now on Spanberger's desk in its original
        form, or about to be.
      </p>

      <div class="bill-grid">
        <!-- BILL 01 — Assault firearms & magazine ban -->
        <article class="bill">
          <div class="bill-top">
            <div class="bill-meta">
              <div class="bill-num">PACKAGE 01</div>
              <div class="bill-ids">HB 217 / SB 749</div>
              <div class="bill-topic topic-2a">
                ASSAULT FIREARM &amp; MAG BAN
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="stamp rejected">Rejected</div>
          </div>
          <div class="bill-body">
            <div class="bill-row">
              <div class="bill-row-lbl">THE BILL</div>
              <div class="bill-row-body">
                Class 1 misdemeanor to import, sell, manufacture, or transfer
                assault firearms and magazines holding more than 15 rounds.
                Lawfully owned firearms and magazines acquired before July 1,
                2026 are grandfathered.
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="bill-row">
              <div class="bill-row-lbl accent-y">SPANBERGER'S AMENDMENT</div>
              <div class="bill-row-body">
                Shifted the ban to a features-based test covering rifles,
                pistols and shotguns. Exempted certain semi-auto hunting
                shotguns. Added a three-year firearm purchase and possession ban
                on anyone convicted under the measure. The critical change: <span
                  class="red">struck the word "fixed"</span
                > from the magazine clause, which critics including the NRA-ILA argue
                expands the ban to common centerfire semi-autos that accept detachable
                magazines over 15 rounds.
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="bill-row">
              <div class="bill-row-lbl accent">APRIL 22 OUTCOME</div>
              <div class="bill-row-body">
                Both chambers <strong>"passed by for the day."</strong> No floor vote,
                no name on the board, procedurally identical to a No. House Democrats
                killed their own governor's substitute without debate.
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="bill-row">
              <div class="bill-row-lbl accent-g">NEXT STEP</div>
              <div class="bill-row-body">
                Bill returns to Spanberger in its <em>original form</em>. She
                can sign the assault weapons ban as the legislature wrote it,
                veto it, or let it become law unsigned. Roughly 30 days on the
                clock.
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </article>

        <!-- BILL 02 — Public carry ban -->
        <article class="bill">
          <div class="bill-top">
            <div class="bill-meta">
              <div class="bill-num">PACKAGE 02</div>
              <div class="bill-ids">HB 1524 / SB 727</div>
              <div class="bill-topic topic-2a">
                PUBLIC CARRY OF "ASSAULT FIREARMS"
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="stamp pending">In block</div>
          </div>
          <div class="bill-body">
            <div class="bill-row">
              <div class="bill-row-lbl">THE BILL</div>
              <div class="bill-row-body">
                Makes it a criminal offense to carry an "assault firearm" in
                most public places (streets, roads, sidewalks, parks, public
                spaces). As enrolled, concealed handgun permit holders were
                <em>not</em> exempt. Amends Va. Code §18.2-287.4.
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="bill-row">
              <div class="bill-row-lbl accent-y">SPANBERGER'S AMENDMENT</div>
              <div class="bill-row-body">
                Pointed the "assault firearm" definition at the broader HB 217 /
                SB 749 substitute, so any expansion there flows through here. <span
                  class="red"
                  >Kept the no-exemption for concealed permit holders</span
                >, meaning permitted carriers remain subject to the ban. Added a
                narrow exemption for cadet corps at public colleges during
                approved training or ceremonial events.
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="bill-row">
              <div class="bill-row-lbl accent">APRIL 22 OUTCOME</div>
              <div class="bill-row-body">
                Not individually covered in same-day reporting. Cardinal News
                and Bearing Arms both reported <strong
                  >20+ amendments rejected as a block</strong
                >, and this bill's definitions are tied directly to HB 217,
                which was rejected. Almost certainly part of the same block
                dispatch.
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="bill-row">
              <div class="bill-row-lbl accent-g">NEXT STEP</div>
              <div class="bill-row-body">
                If rejected, goes back to Spanberger in original form. Either a
                public-carry ban on named assault firearms becomes law without
                her features-based expansion, or she vetoes a bill her own
                caucus just insisted on. The underlying permit-holder exposure
                is unchanged either way.
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </article>

        <!-- BILL 03 — UBC + age alignment + emergency clause -->
        <article class="bill">
          <div class="bill-top">
            <div class="bill-meta">
              <div class="bill-num">PACKAGE 03</div>
              <div class="bill-ids">HB 1525</div>
              <div class="bill-topic topic-2a">UBC + 18-TO-21 AGE HIKE</div>
            </div>
            <div class="stamp pending">In block</div>
          </div>
          <div class="bill-body">
            <div class="bill-row">
              <div class="bill-row-lbl">THE BILL</div>
              <div class="bill-row-body">
                Restores universal background checks on private firearm sales
                after a Lynchburg court ruling ended enforcement of the earlier
                state mandate. Raises the minimum purchase age for handguns and
                certain covered firearms from 18 to 21, with exceptions for
                military and law enforcement.
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="bill-row">
              <div class="bill-row-lbl accent-y">SPANBERGER'S AMENDMENT</div>
              <div class="bill-row-body">
                Directed Virginia State Police to resume private-sale checks,
                aligned the age-21 floor explicitly with federal law, and added
                an <strong>emergency clause</strong> so the law would take effect
                on passage rather than July 1. The emergency clause is the procedural
                pressure point.
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="bill-row">
              <div class="bill-row-lbl accent">APRIL 22 OUTCOME</div>
              <div class="bill-row-body">
                Not broken out individually in same-day reporting. An emergency
                clause requires a <strong>four-fifths</strong> vote in each chamber,
                which Democrats alone can't hit. If the emergency clause fails, the
                underlying amendment can still be rejected by simple majority. Most
                likely part of the broad rejection block.
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="bill-row">
              <div class="bill-row-lbl accent-g">NEXT STEP</div>
              <div class="bill-row-body">
                If rejected, the original bill goes back to Spanberger with the
                standard July 1 effective date and without her age-alignment
                language. GOA has signaled litigation over the private-sale
                background check regardless of final form.
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </article>

        <!-- BILL 04 — Firearms in mental health hospitals -->
        <article class="bill">
          <div class="bill-top">
            <div class="bill-meta">
              <div class="bill-num">PACKAGE 04</div>
              <div class="bill-ids">HB 229 / SB 173</div>
              <div class="bill-topic topic-2a">
                WEAPONS IN MENTAL HEALTH HOSPITALS
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="stamp pending">In block</div>
          </div>
          <div class="bill-body">
            <div class="bill-row">
              <div class="bill-row-lbl">THE BILL</div>
              <div class="bill-row-body">
                Class 1 misdemeanor to knowingly possess a firearm, a knife with
                a blade over 3.5 inches, or other dangerous weapon inside any
                hospital building that provides mental health or developmental
                services, including emergency departments. Seized weapons
                forfeited to the Commonwealth.
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="bill-row">
              <div class="bill-row-lbl accent-y">SPANBERGER'S AMENDMENT</div>
              <div class="bill-row-body">
                <span class="red"
                  >Stripped the written-authorization exception</span
                >. As enrolled, the bill carved out anyone with written
                permission from hospital administrators (including security
                personnel and employees). Spanberger's substitute eliminates
                that path entirely. Hospitals can no longer authorize armed
                staff or private security on mental health campuses.
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="bill-row">
              <div class="bill-row-lbl accent">APRIL 22 OUTCOME</div>
              <div class="bill-row-body">
                Not individually detailed in same-day reporting, but listed by
                NRA-ILA as one of the four headline amended gun bills. Likely
                part of the same block of rejected amendments.
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="bill-row">
              <div class="bill-row-lbl accent-g">NEXT STEP</div>
              <div class="bill-row-body">
                If rejected, the original bill with the written-permission
                exception returns to Spanberger. Hospitals retain the authority
                to let designated employees or contract security carry on their
                property, which is what her amendment tried to close.
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </article>

        <!-- BILL 05 — Safe storage -->
        <article class="bill">
          <div class="bill-top">
            <div class="bill-meta">
              <div class="bill-num">PACKAGE 05</div>
              <div class="bill-ids">HB 871 / SB 348</div>
              <div class="bill-topic topic-2a">
                SAFE STORAGE (HOMES WITH MINORS)
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="stamp pending">Pending</div>
          </div>
          <div class="bill-body">
            <div class="bill-row">
              <div class="bill-row-lbl">THE BILL</div>
              <div class="bill-row-body">
                Requires firearms in homes where minors are present to be kept
                in "a locked container, compartment, or cabinet" that is
                inaccessible to the minor. Enforcement tied to civil penalties
                and aggravating-factor treatment for downstream offenses.
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="bill-row">
              <div class="bill-row-lbl accent-y">SPANBERGER'S AMENDMENT</div>
              <div class="bill-row-body">
                Expanded the safe-storage definition to include a firearm
                rendered inoperable by a dedicated locking device (trigger lock,
                cable lock). A genuine concession: the enrolled bill required
                physical containment, and trigger-locked firearms were arguably
                non-compliant.
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="bill-row">
              <div class="bill-row-lbl accent">APRIL 22 OUTCOME</div>
              <div class="bill-row-body">
                Not flagged as a fight in same-day reporting. This was the least
                adversarial of her firearm amendments and the one gun-rights
                groups didn't attack. Plausibly accepted, though not confirmed.
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="bill-row">
              <div class="bill-row-lbl accent-g">NEXT STEP</div>
              <div class="bill-row-body">
                If accepted, trigger-locked firearms count as compliant when the
                law takes effect July 1. If rejected, the tighter
                containment-only version goes back to the governor.
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </article>

        <!-- BILL 06 — Gun buyback programs -->
        <article class="bill">
          <div class="bill-top">
            <div class="bill-meta">
              <div class="bill-num">PACKAGE 06</div>
              <div class="bill-ids">HB 702</div>
              <div class="bill-topic topic-2a">LOCAL GUN BUY-BACK PROGRAMS</div>
            </div>
            <div class="stamp pending">Pending</div>
          </div>
          <div class="bill-body">
            <div class="bill-row">
              <div class="bill-row-lbl">THE BILL</div>
              <div class="bill-row-body">
                Authorizes Virginia localities to stand up voluntary gun
                buy-back programs where residents can turn in firearms in
                exchange for compensation.
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="bill-row">
              <div class="bill-row-lbl accent-y">SPANBERGER'S AMENDMENT</div>
              <div class="bill-row-body">
                Technical language clarifying that buy-back programs exist "to
                provide a safe process" for residents who choose to return a
                firearm. No operational teeth, no enforcement change, no budget
                implications. The smallest of her six gun amendments.
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="bill-row">
              <div class="bill-row-lbl accent">APRIL 22 OUTCOME</div>
              <div class="bill-row-body">
                Not flagged as contested. Technical amendments of this scale are
                usually rubber-stamped even in a hostile reconvened session.
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="bill-row">
              <div class="bill-row-lbl accent-g">NEXT STEP</div>
              <div class="bill-row-body">
                Either way, the authorization for local buy-back programs moves
                forward. Richmond, Norfolk, and NoVA localities now have a
                standing lane to spend local funds buying firearms off the
                street.
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- EDITORIAL: WHAT THIS MEANS FOR 2A -->
    <section class="section">
      <div class="section-label">
        <span class="num">03 /</span> THE 2A READ
      </div>
      <h2 class="section-title">
        The assault weapons ban is <span class="red">on her desk</span>.
      </h2>
      <p class="section-deck">
        Strip away the other five gun packages and this is the one fight that
        defines her governorship. The House just took her exit ramps away.
      </p>

      <div class="callout">
        <div class="callout-quote">
          Spanberger's three-option menu is now a <span class="red"
            >two-option trap</span
          >: sign what her own party wrote, or veto and take the
          <span class="gold">hit</span>.
        </div>
        <div class="callout-body">
          <p>
            Her amendments were the face-saving version. By removing the word
            "fixed" from the magazine clause, she handed the original ban more
            teeth than the sponsors had written in, while giving herself a
            political hedge to point at shotgun exemptions and feature
            clarifications. The House passed it by without a vote. No hedge. No
            cover.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>Option one:</strong> she signs HB 217 / SB 749 as the legislature
            passed it. Virginia becomes the next state with an active assault weapons
            ban, the DOJ lawsuit threats turn into actual filings, and Bruen-era litigation
            starts almost immediately.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>Option two:</strong> she vetoes. The ban dies. Her own caucus,
            the same caucus that killed her amendments yesterday, watches its signature
            2026 policy win evaporate because their governor couldn't take yes for
            an answer. Override needs 2/3 of each chamber. Democrats don't have that
            alone.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>Option three doesn't exist anymore.</strong> The House made sure
            of that.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="matrix">
        <div class="matrix-cell red">
          <div class="matrix-head">SCENARIO A</div>
          <div class="matrix-title">She signs the ban</div>
          <div class="matrix-body">
            Virginia joins the active AWB states. Grandfathered pre-July 2026
            firearms. DOJ litigation threats materialize. Court challenges from
            VCDL and GOA start in the Eastern District. 2A community
            mobilization goes vertical.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="matrix-cell gold">
          <div class="matrix-head">SCENARIO B</div>
          <div class="matrix-title">She vetoes it</div>
          <div class="matrix-body">
            Ban dies. Dem caucus faces a brutal civil war between the governor's
            office and General Assembly leadership. Override vote would need
            roughly 67 House votes and 27 Senate. Dems don't have it alone.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="matrix-cell green">
          <div class="matrix-head">SCENARIO C</div>
          <div class="matrix-title">She lets it become law</div>
          <div class="matrix-body">
            No signature, no veto. After 30 days the bill becomes law anyway.
            She gets the policy without a signing ceremony. Politically clean.
            The weakest governor choice, and probably the most likely.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- BIGGER PICTURE -->
    <section class="section">
      <div class="section-label">
        <span class="num">04 /</span> THE BIGGER STORY
      </div>
      <h2 class="section-title">
        Democrats just <span class="red">publicly broke</span> with their own governor.
      </h2>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          Keep in mind the math. Democrats control the House
          <strong>51-49</strong> and the Senate <strong>21-19</strong>. They
          don't need a single Republican to pass or reject anything in a
          majority vote. Everything that happened yesterday happened <em
            >inside the majority</em
          >.
        </p>
        <p>
          Reporting from Cardinal News, WVTF, and Virginia Mercury tells the
          same story: Democratic lawmakers complained Spanberger sent back too
          many bills with too little warning, made substantive rewrites (not
          technical cleanup), and did it without consulting bill sponsors. On
          the assault firearm ban specifically, removing "fixed" from the
          magazine clause was never what the sponsors wrote. The House killed it
          without even taking a vote.
        </p>
        <p>
          This isn't a split between parties. It's a split between
          <strong>legislative Democrats</strong> who spent years negotiating these
          bills and an <strong>executive Democrat</strong> who tried to rewrite them
          with a pen on April 13. That matters for the next four years of Virginia
          politics, not just the 2A fight.
        </p>
        <p>
          For gun owners, the upside is narrow but real. The governor's own
          party just told her: <em>take what we gave you, or take the loss</em>.
          Every scenario now produces a cleaner political fact on the record
          than her amended version would have.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- CTA -->
    <section class="cta">
      <div class="cta-inner">
        <div class="cta-kicker">WATCH THE NEXT 30 DAYS</div>
        <h2>HB 217 IS<br />ON HER DESK.</h2>
        <p>
          By roughly May 22 Spanberger has to sign, veto, or let it become law.
          The other rejected packages run the same clock. Every one of them is a
          test of whether a Democratic governor will break with her caucus to
          cover for her own amendments, or swallow the bills she publicly
          rewrote.
        </p>
